1
00:01:10,926 --> 00:01:12,087
In 1970,

2
00:01:12,394 --> 00:01:13,486
Taiwan's foreign trade

3
00:01:13,729 --> 00:01:15,356
enjoyed a trade surplus
for the first time.

4
00:01:15,564 --> 00:01:16,531
Major export products included

5
00:01:16,765 --> 00:01:19,928
electronics, plastics, and machinery,

6
00:01:20,402 --> 00:01:22,063
as the focus of industrial development

7
00:01:22,271 --> 00:01:24,069
in Taiwan transformed gradually.

8
00:01:24,406 --> 00:01:25,737
Although economic growth

9
00:01:26,041 --> 00:01:27,031
had exceeded 11 percent

10
00:01:27,342 --> 00:01:29,003
for four years running,

11
00:01:29,444 --> 00:01:31,310
the international situation was starting

12
00:01:31,546 --> 00:01:33,708
to undergo tremendous changes.

13
00:01:34,049 --> 00:01:35,039
As a series of

14
00:01:35,350 --> 00:01:35,816
diplomatic setbacks

15
00:01:36,051 --> 00:01:38,520
befell Taiwan,

16
00:01:38,887 --> 00:01:40,184
the history of the Taiwan people

17
00:01:40,422 --> 00:01:42,754
again underwent dramatic changes.

18
00:01:50,666 --> 00:01:52,828
On Oct. 25, 1971,

19
00:01:53,068 --> 00:01:54,695
Albania proposed draft resolution
No. 2758,

20
00:01:54,937 --> 00:01:55,802
calling for the admission
of the PRC and expulsion

21
00:01:56,071 --> 00:01:59,405
of the representatives of
Chiang Kai-shek from the U.N.

22
00:01:59,574 --> 00:02:02,043
As the draft resolution
was put to vote,

23
00:02:02,477 --> 00:02:04,844
then foreign minister Chou Shu-kai,

24
00:02:05,080 --> 00:02:06,809
knowing the vote result in advance,

25
00:02:07,082 --> 00:02:09,346
announced Taiwan's withdrawal
from the U.N.

26
00:02:09,518 --> 00:02:11,816
before the voting started.

27
00:02:16,725 --> 00:02:18,625
Faced with such disastrous impact,

28
00:02:18,860 --> 00:02:21,557
Chiang Kai-shek in his
address to the nation

29
00:02:21,797 --> 00:02:23,526
denounced the U.N.
General Assembly

30
00:02:23,765 --> 00:02:26,291
for undermining the U.N.
Charter and principles.

31
00:02:26,601 --> 00:02:28,865
Government agencies
and the media also

32
00:02:29,104 --> 00:02:30,799
joined in protest activities

33
00:02:31,039 --> 00:02:32,905
throughout Taiwan.

34
00:03:02,904 --> 00:03:04,235
In February 1972,

35
00:03:04,473 --> 00:03:06,908
U.S. President Nixon visited the PRC.

36
00:03:07,142 --> 00:03:10,043
The U.S. and the PRC jointly issued

37
00:03:10,212 --> 00:03:12,112
the Shanghai Communiqué,
which once again upset

38
00:03:12,381 --> 00:03:14,349
the international status of Taiwan.

39
00:03:21,390 --> 00:03:23,586
Our two peoples tonight

40
00:03:24,092 --> 00:03:27,494
hold the future of the world
in our hands.

41
00:03:27,729 --> 00:03:29,595
And as we think about the future,

42
00:03:31,333 --> 00:03:36,430
we are dedicated to a principle that

43
00:03:36,671 --> 00:03:38,002
we can build a new world,
a world of peace,

44
00:03:38,240 --> 00:03:39,901
a world of justice,

45
00:03:40,175 --> 00:03:42,200
a world of independence...

46
00:03:42,444 --> 00:03:43,343
Withdrawal from the U.N.

47
00:03:43,578 --> 00:03:45,808
adversely affected

48
00:03:46,048 --> 00:03:48,312
Taiwan's diplomatic relations
and international status.

49
00:03:48,550 --> 00:03:49,847
Pres. Nixon's visit to the PRC

50
00:03:50,085 --> 00:03:52,486
further set in motion
a series of events.

51
00:03:52,788 --> 00:03:54,517
The number of countries with
diplomatic ties to Taiwan

52
00:03:54,756 --> 00:03:56,053
gradually diminished.

53
00:03:56,658 --> 00:03:58,023
Even Japan, once a major ally,

54
00:03:58,226 --> 00:04:00,593
also severed ties with Taiwan

55
00:04:00,829 --> 00:04:02,456
on Sept. 29, 1972.

56
00:04:02,764 --> 00:04:05,062
Before severing ties with Taiwan,

57
00:04:05,367 --> 00:04:08,132
Japan had sent special envoy
Etsusaburo Shiina to Taiwan.

58
00:04:08,370 --> 00:04:10,498
But his visit sparked off
severe protests.

59
00:04:10,806 --> 00:04:12,501
After Japan severed ties
with Taiwan,

60
00:04:12,741 --> 00:04:14,334
many Taiwan organizations initiated

61
00:04:14,509 --> 00:04:17,035
movements to boycott Japan;

62
00:04:17,279 --> 00:04:18,838
but these movements did not last long.

63
00:04:19,448 --> 00:04:21,109
Apart from setbacks in
foreign relations,

64
00:04:21,383 --> 00:04:23,750
Taiwan also experienced
problems in economic growth

65
00:04:23,985 --> 00:04:26,386
during the early 1970s.

66
00:04:26,621 --> 00:04:27,315
Statistics show that

67
00:04:27,556 --> 00:04:29,684
the number of immigrants
applying to leave Taiwan

68
00:04:29,925 --> 00:04:31,984
in 1972 increased eight-fold
from previous years.

69
00:04:33,395 --> 00:04:34,453
In 1973,

70
00:04:34,696 --> 00:04:36,095
the Fourth Middle East War

71
00:04:36,331 --> 00:04:38,459
resulted in the first oil crisis.

72
00:04:38,700 --> 00:04:40,395
The decline of the world economy

73
00:04:40,635 --> 00:04:42,535
was yet another blow to Taiwan,

74
00:04:42,771 --> 00:04:45,172
which was dependent on
foreign trade.

75
00:04:57,052 --> 00:04:59,487
In the evening of April 5, 1975,

76
00:04:59,654 --> 00:05:00,678
Chiang Kai-shek, whose

77
00:05:00,922 --> 00:05:03,186
authoritarian rule of Taiwan
lasted 25 years,

78
00:05:03,425 --> 00:05:06,326
passed away during
this critical period.

79
00:05:06,528 --> 00:05:07,188
He left the difficult problems

80
00:05:07,429 --> 00:05:10,399
to his son Chiang Ching-kuo
and the people of Taiwan.

81
00:05:22,444 --> 00:05:24,412
On the day following Chiang's death,

82
00:05:24,646 --> 00:05:27,274
the government declared
a month of mourning.

83
00:05:27,582 --> 00:05:30,608
Students were taught songs
in memory of Chiang.

84
00:05:30,886 --> 00:05:32,752
Employees in the military,
government, and the academia

85
00:05:33,021 --> 00:05:35,490
were asked to put on
black armbands.

86
00:05:35,724 --> 00:05:37,283
Flags in the military,
government, and schools

87
00:05:37,459 --> 00:05:39,587
flew at half-mast for one month.

88
00:05:39,828 --> 00:05:42,456
Entertainment establishments
were suspended for one month.

89
00:05:42,697 --> 00:05:44,791
All newspapers were printed
only in black and white.

90
00:05:45,033 --> 00:05:47,661
The three TV networks aired
programs in black and white.

91
00:05:47,903 --> 00:05:49,166
After the death of Chiang Kai-shek

92
00:05:49,404 --> 00:05:51,133
and with strict government control,

93
00:05:51,373 --> 00:05:54,308
the whole nation was engulfed
in an atmosphere of mourning.

94
00:05:54,476 --> 00:05:56,774
An old era has ended
with Chiang's death.

95
00:05:57,045 --> 00:05:59,104
Yet the new era of Chiang Ching-kuo

96
00:05:59,347 --> 00:06:00,872
also began.

97
00:06:09,791 --> 00:06:11,316
After the KMT government

98
00:06:11,526 --> 00:06:13,790
retreated to Taiwan
from the mainland,

99
00:06:14,062 --> 00:06:15,120
Chaing Kai-shek had started to groom

100
00:06:15,363 --> 00:06:18,094
his son Chiang Ching-kuo as successor.

101
00:06:18,567 --> 00:06:20,399
In 1949, Chiang Ching-kuo,

102
00:06:20,635 --> 00:06:22,194
under order of Chiang Kai-shek,

103
00:06:22,437 --> 00:06:24,496
was in charge of moving gold
stocked in the mainland

104
00:06:24,739 --> 00:06:26,104
to Taiwan.

105
00:06:26,374 --> 00:06:29,344
In 1950, he became head of
General Political Department

106
00:06:29,578 --> 00:06:32,172
to control political affairs
and intelligence work.

107
00:06:32,414 --> 00:06:34,314
He later became head of
Veterans Affairs Commission,

108
00:06:34,549 --> 00:06:35,880
a minister without portfolio

109
00:06:36,117 --> 00:06:37,881
and defense minister.

110
00:06:38,153 --> 00:06:41,179
In 1970, Chiang became vice premier,

111
00:06:41,423 --> 00:06:43,824
and in 1972, premier.

112
00:06:44,092 --> 00:06:46,527
Chiang wielded absolute power.

113
00:06:51,099 --> 00:06:52,624
Having studied in Moscow

114
00:06:52,867 --> 00:06:54,892
and joined the Communist Party,

115
00:06:55,136 --> 00:06:56,661
Chiang, unlike his father,

116
00:06:56,905 --> 00:06:58,669
was hot obsessed with
retaking the mainland.

117
00:06:58,907 --> 00:07:00,671
He was more pragmatic

118
00:07:00,909 --> 00:07:03,139
in face of Taiwan's political
environment.

119
00:07:03,478 --> 00:07:05,742
Chiang began to employ
elite Taiwanese politicians

120
00:07:06,047 --> 00:07:08,072
such as Hsieh Tung-min,
Lin Yang-kang,

121
00:07:08,350 --> 00:07:10,614
Lee Teng-hui,
and Chiu Chuang-huan,

122
00:07:11,052 --> 00:07:13,680
which was seen as the start
of indigenization in Taiwan.

123
00:07:22,664 --> 00:07:24,758
On Dec. 16, 1973,

124
00:07:25,066 --> 00:07:26,397
Chiang Ching-kuo announced

125
00:07:26,635 --> 00:07:27,966
a plan to complete the ten
major infrastructure projects

126
00:07:28,136 --> 00:07:30,366
within five years.

127
00:07:30,639 --> 00:07:32,107
Finance and economic
officials of mainland descent

128
00:07:32,340 --> 00:07:34,069
such as Li Kuo-ting, Yen Chia-kan,

129
00:07:34,309 --> 00:07:35,299
and Sun Yun-syuan

130
00:07:35,543 --> 00:07:36,066
were assigned this vital task

131
00:07:36,311 --> 00:07:39,076
of Taiwan's economic transformation.

132
00:07:39,881 --> 00:07:41,849
The successful completion of
the ten major infrastructure

133
00:07:42,083 --> 00:07:42,641
projects, along with the

134
00:07:42,884 --> 00:07:45,410
gradual revival of the
global economy,

135
00:07:45,654 --> 00:07:47,315
enabled Taiwan to survive

136
00:07:47,555 --> 00:07:49,114
the first Oil Crisis

137
00:07:49,357 --> 00:07:51,758
and facilitated the growth of
Taiwan's economy.

138
00:07:52,027 --> 00:07:54,359
Local small and medium enterprises,

139
00:07:54,596 --> 00:07:56,496
with their aggressiveness and
flexible production methods,

140
00:07:56,731 --> 00:07:58,130
started to gain prominence
in the international market.

141
00:07:58,366 --> 00:08:00,858
Taiwan's production model
based on dual economy

142
00:08:01,102 --> 00:08:04,003
thus became a model for
other developing countries.

143
00:08:12,347 --> 00:08:14,042
To alleviate the resentment
of local Taiwanese for

144
00:08:14,349 --> 00:08:16,545
being excluded from central
government policy-making,

145
00:08:16,785 --> 00:08:18,184
Chiang amended the
Temporary Provisions during

146
00:08:18,420 --> 00:08:21,481
the Period of Mobilization
against Communist Rebellion

147
00:08:21,723 --> 00:08:24,420
and called for elections
starting at the end of 1972

148
00:08:24,659 --> 00:08:26,320
for additional National
Assembly representatives,

149
00:08:26,561 --> 00:08:29,553
who were frozen in office
for the last 25 years.

150
00:08:30,098 --> 00:08:30,656
Although these newly

151
00:08:30,899 --> 00:08:33,061
elected representatives accounted for

152
00:08:33,301 --> 00:08:35,963
only a small minority
in the National Assembly,

153
00:08:36,137 --> 00:08:38,128
the election paved the way

154
00:08:38,373 --> 00:08:40,535
for a new democratic movement
in Taiwan.

155
00:08:47,449 --> 00:08:48,814
There was a heightened
sense of awareness of

156
00:08:49,050 --> 00:08:51,985
local cultures during
Chiang's administration.

157
00:08:52,520 --> 00:08:54,045
In September 1973

158
00:08:54,322 --> 00:08:57,292
Cloud Gate Dance Theatre
established by Lin Huai-min

159
00:08:57,525 --> 00:08:58,651
brought an all-new

160
00:08:58,893 --> 00:09:00,725
cultural experience to Taiwan.

161
00:09:01,129 --> 00:09:02,028
Every performance

162
00:09:02,330 --> 00:09:04,128
attracted positive and
enthusiastic feedbacks.

163
00:09:16,378 --> 00:09:17,402
In 1975,

164
00:09:17,645 --> 00:09:20,546
Yang Hsien, Hu Te-fu,
and Li Shuang-tse

165
00:09:20,782 --> 00:09:23,114
launched a folk song
movement, as the start of

166
00:09:23,385 --> 00:09:26,548
a new era looking
for the people's roots.

167
00:09:26,788 --> 00:09:27,880
Singing one's own songs

168
00:09:28,123 --> 00:09:30,251
became a fad among students,

169
00:09:30,492 --> 00:09:33,462
bringing the popularization
of folk songs in schools.

170
00:09:46,608 --> 00:09:48,474
In addition, folk arts,

171
00:09:48,710 --> 00:09:50,735
both traditional or contemporary,

172
00:09:50,979 --> 00:09:52,845
started to receive widespread
attention

173
00:09:53,081 --> 00:09:55,550
in local intellectual circles.

174
00:09:56,484 --> 00:09:58,680
These are all results of
efforts by cultural elites,

175
00:09:58,920 --> 00:10:01,252
intellectuals, and young students who

176
00:10:01,489 --> 00:10:04,857
recognized the importance
of local culture.

177
00:10:05,093 --> 00:10:06,390
Who are we?

178
00:10:06,628 --> 00:10:07,993
What is Taiwan?

179
00:10:08,329 --> 00:10:10,559
Influenced by Chinese
and U.S. cultures

180
00:10:10,799 --> 00:10:13,359
for a quarter of a century,
the people of Taiwan

181
00:10:13,635 --> 00:10:16,627
wanted to rediscover
their lost identity.

182
00:10:16,871 --> 00:10:22,776
They cautioned repeatedly.

183
00:10:23,011 --> 00:10:25,776
Do not forget.

184
00:10:26,014 --> 00:10:28,881
Do not forget.

185
00:10:29,117 --> 00:10:34,920
They cautioned repeatedly.

186
00:10:35,156 --> 00:10:38,057
There is much hardship
in the establishment

187
00:10:38,359 --> 00:10:41,795
of a foundation.

188
00:10:43,064 --> 00:10:45,931
Native literature came into
existence accordingly.

189
00:10:46,167 --> 00:10:48,397
A group of Taiwan-born
young writers

190
00:10:48,636 --> 00:10:50,832
started to write about the
ordinary people around them

191
00:10:51,072 --> 00:10:52,870
and their experiences growing up.

192
00:10:53,107 --> 00:10:53,801
They further criticized the

193
00:10:54,042 --> 00:10:56,704
unfairness, unjustness,
and absurdity in the island.

194
00:11:08,256 --> 00:11:10,088
Following the Taiwan
native literature movement,

195
00:11:10,391 --> 00:11:11,722
a wave of new Taiwan movies

196
00:11:11,960 --> 00:11:13,792
proliferated in the 1980s.

197
00:11:14,095 --> 00:11:15,358
The movies criticized and
provided introspection on

198
00:11:15,597 --> 00:11:16,655
the mindset during the 1950s

199
00:11:16,898 --> 00:11:18,866
and 1960s, which gravitated

200
00:11:19,100 --> 00:11:21,228
towards Chinese
and American cultures.

201
00:11:21,870 --> 00:11:23,360
The young movie-makers

202
00:11:23,605 --> 00:11:24,572
attempted to establish a

203
00:11:24,806 --> 00:11:28,003
new Taiwan experience
and aesthetic concept.

204
00:11:29,043 --> 00:11:30,636
The movie
The Sandwich Man

205
00:11:30,879 --> 00:11:33,780
was an adaptation of a
novel by Huang Chun-ming.

206
00:11:34,048 --> 00:11:36,483
It was an important
collective work by the

207
00:11:36,718 --> 00:11:38,812
post-war baby boomers
about the Taiwan experience.

208
00:11:39,220 --> 00:11:41,814
The movie gained prominence
in international film festivals.

209
00:11:42,156 --> 00:11:44,625
Taiwan, the small island,

210
00:11:44,859 --> 00:11:47,385
lacking in identity throughout history,

211
00:11:47,629 --> 00:11:49,188
finally received
international attention

212
00:11:49,430 --> 00:11:51,626
because of the new movie movement.

213
00:12:12,420 --> 00:12:13,683
Apart from the diplomatic setbacks

214
00:12:13,922 --> 00:12:15,253
during the 1970s,

215
00:12:15,490 --> 00:12:16,582
the administration likewise

216
00:12:16,824 --> 00:12:19,122
faced the prospect of
power transition.

217
00:12:19,394 --> 00:12:20,793
The clamor for political reform

218
00:12:21,095 --> 00:12:23,359
started to brew

219
00:12:23,565 --> 00:12:25,260
through student political discussions

220
00:12:25,433 --> 00:12:27,094
in college magazines

221
00:12:27,435 --> 00:12:30,302
and the emergence of
Taiwan-born political figures

222
00:12:30,505 --> 00:12:32,064
through local elections.

223
00:12:32,340 --> 00:12:34,707
This resulted in civil movements

224
00:12:35,043 --> 00:12:37,011
by members of the opposition.

225
00:12:37,211 --> 00:12:38,701
After several elections,

226
00:12:38,947 --> 00:12:40,039
the movement gradually transformed

227
00:12:40,348 --> 00:12:42,146
into a political opposition.

228
00:12:50,124 --> 00:12:51,216
In 1977,

229
00:12:51,459 --> 00:12:52,358
Taiwan for the first time

230
00:12:52,594 --> 00:12:55,086
held elections for five local offices.

231
00:12:55,363 --> 00:12:57,627
Hsu Hsin-liang, without KMT
nomination, ran for the

232
00:12:57,865 --> 00:12:59,663
election for Taoyuan county
magistrate on his own.

233
00:12:59,968 --> 00:13:02,027
Hsu was subsequently expelled
from the KMT,

234
00:13:02,203 --> 00:13:03,864
and became a member
of the opposition.

235
00:13:04,372 --> 00:13:06,841
On Nov. 19, Election Day,

236
00:13:07,075 --> 00:13:09,737
the supervisor of the 213

237
00:13:09,978 --> 00:13:11,503
ballot center in Chungli City

238
00:13:11,746 --> 00:13:13,578
allegedly tampered the

239
00:13:13,815 --> 00:13:15,146
ballots cast in favor of Hsu.

240
00:13:15,383 --> 00:13:17,351
The public filed complaints
on the spot,

241
00:13:17,752 --> 00:13:19,345
and conflict ensued between
the two parties.

242
00:13:19,587 --> 00:13:21,487
In the end, Hsu's supporters

243
00:13:21,723 --> 00:13:23,213
surrounded the Chungli police station,

244
00:13:23,458 --> 00:13:24,357
vandalized police cars,

245
00:13:24,525 --> 00:13:26,425
and set fire to the police station.

246
00:13:26,661 --> 00:13:29,153
This was the
Chungli Incident, which had

247
00:13:29,397 --> 00:13:31,729
significant impact on later
democratic movements.

248
00:13:37,138 --> 00:13:38,765
The Chungli Incident was
the first time

249
00:13:39,040 --> 00:13:40,872
that the public voluntarily
marched in the streets

250
00:13:41,109 --> 00:13:42,372
in protest of election fraud,

251
00:13:42,610 --> 00:13:45,102
and was a prelude to
street movements.

252
00:13:45,747 --> 00:13:48,011
The opposition had gained momentum

253
00:13:48,182 --> 00:13:49,479
throughout Taiwan.

254
00:13:49,717 --> 00:13:53,119
In the public official election in 1978,

255
00:13:53,354 --> 00:13:54,844
opposition candidates

256
00:13:55,089 --> 00:13:58,457
often drew large, fanatic crowds.

257
00:14:00,261 --> 00:14:01,660
The election, however,

258
00:14:01,896 --> 00:14:02,886
was cancelled by Chiang Ching-kuo

259
00:14:03,131 --> 00:14:04,394
after the U.S. announced

260
00:14:04,632 --> 00:14:05,929
that it had established diplomatic ties

261
00:14:06,167 --> 00:14:08,431
with the PRC.

262
00:14:10,605 --> 00:14:11,697
After the R.O.C. and the U.S.
severed diplomatic ties,

263
00:14:11,939 --> 00:14:13,805
U.S. Deputy State Secretary,
Warren Christopher,

264
00:14:14,075 --> 00:14:16,601
arrived in Taiwan to discuss
issues after the fact.

265
00:14:16,911 --> 00:14:20,040
Foreign Minister Fred Chien
issued a strong statement,

266
00:14:20,214 --> 00:14:23,047
and the Taiwan people also
unleashed strong protests.

267
00:14:23,518 --> 00:14:24,576
This was yet another
enormous setback

268
00:14:24,819 --> 00:14:26,116
in diplomatic relations
of the KMT government

269
00:14:26,354 --> 00:14:28,652
after withdrawal from the U.N.

270
00:14:28,890 --> 00:14:31,757
This was also a turning point
in Taiwan politics.

271
00:14:32,226 --> 00:14:33,284
The opposition

272
00:14:33,528 --> 00:14:34,996
was forced to reassess
the situation due to

273
00:14:35,196 --> 00:14:36,561
the sudden cancellation of the election.

274
00:14:36,798 --> 00:14:38,163
They discussed counter-strategies.

275
00:14:38,766 --> 00:14:40,996
On Dec. 25, a senior member
of the opposition,

276
00:14:41,202 --> 00:14:42,727
Yu Teng-fa,

277
00:14:43,037 --> 00:14:44,368
led the signing of

278
00:14:44,605 --> 00:14:47,597
a declaration on the state of
the nation by the opposition.

279
00:14:47,842 --> 00:14:49,332
The declaration stressed

280
00:14:49,877 --> 00:14:51,675
strong opposition to the
use of force by any

281
00:14:51,913 --> 00:14:54,814
hegemony to dictate the
destiny of the Taiwan people.

282
00:14:55,049 --> 00:14:56,915
The declaration maintained
that the future

283
00:14:57,151 --> 00:14:58,448
of Taiwan should be jointly
determined

284
00:14:58,686 --> 00:15:00,313
by its 17 million people.

285
00:15:04,592 --> 00:15:06,686
The year after the
declaration was issued,

286
00:15:06,928 --> 00:15:09,192
on Jan. 21, 1979,

287
00:15:09,430 --> 00:15:11,899
the KMT arrested Yu Teng-fa

288
00:15:12,133 --> 00:15:15,194
and his son Yu Jui-yen
on charges of sedition.

289
00:15:15,436 --> 00:15:17,029
The arrest prompted the opposition

290
00:15:17,238 --> 00:15:18,763
to march in Kaohsiung County

291
00:15:19,073 --> 00:15:20,734
in protest.

292
00:15:21,142 --> 00:15:22,200
This was the first protest march

293
00:15:22,443 --> 00:15:24,207
by the opposition.

294
00:15:24,712 --> 00:15:25,838
Thereafter, the opposition began

295
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:28,344
to use outdoor gatherings

296
00:15:28,583 --> 00:15:29,812
to promote their cause.

297
00:15:30,051 --> 00:15:31,815
Street protests became frequent.

298
00:15:39,627 --> 00:15:40,992
Two major

299
00:15:41,162 --> 00:15:42,596
opposition magazines

300
00:15:42,830 --> 00:15:45,094
started publication in 1979.

301
00:15:45,333 --> 00:15:47,427
One was The Eighties Magazine.

302
00:15:47,668 --> 00:15:49,636
The other was Formosa Magazine.

303
00:15:49,904 --> 00:15:50,803
The Formosa Magazine

304
00:15:51,038 --> 00:15:52,506
gathered members of the
opposition as staff members

305
00:15:52,740 --> 00:15:55,038
and helped organized the opposition.

306
00:15:55,343 --> 00:15:57,812
In fact, the magazine was a
rudimentary political party.

307
00:15:58,212 --> 00:15:58,804
It gathered members of the

308
00:15:59,046 --> 00:16:01,014
opposition island-wide

309
00:16:01,249 --> 00:16:04,082
and organized public speeches.

310
00:16:04,418 --> 00:16:07,149
Tension between the ruling
and the opposition escalated.

311
00:16:07,588 --> 00:16:09,852
By the end of 1979,

312
00:16:10,091 --> 00:16:12,423
the Formosa Incident broke out.

313
00:16:20,802 --> 00:16:22,497
Long live human rights!

314
00:16:22,904 --> 00:16:24,099
Long live human rights!

315
00:16:24,372 --> 00:16:25,771
Long live peace!

316
00:16:26,007 --> 00:16:27,372
Long live peace!

317
00:16:27,642 --> 00:16:29,303
We want peace!

318
00:16:29,544 --> 00:16:30,978
We want peace!

319
00:16:31,212 --> 00:16:32,771
We want human rights!

320
00:16:33,014 --> 00:16:34,504
We want human rights!

321
00:16:34,782 --> 00:16:36,841
Long life human rights!

322
00:16:37,752 --> 00:16:39,618
Dec. 10, 1979 is

323
00:16:39,854 --> 00:16:41,151
Human Rights Day

324
00:16:41,422 --> 00:16:42,355
In that evening,

325
00:16:42,590 --> 00:16:44,786
members of the opposition
assembled in Kaohsiung City

326
00:16:45,026 --> 00:16:47,688
as scheduled to celebrate
Human Rights Day.

327
00:16:48,029 --> 00:16:50,999
The administration deployed
large contingents of police.

328
00:16:51,699 --> 00:16:53,497
Shih Ming-de,
the coordinator of the assembly,

329
00:16:53,734 --> 00:16:55,998
learned that the assembly ground

330
00:16:56,170 --> 00:16:58,002
had been sealed off by the police

331
00:16:58,172 --> 00:17:00,038
and decided to change
the speaking venue

332
00:17:00,341 --> 00:17:03,709
to the traffic circle
in Hsinhsing District.

333
00:17:04,045 --> 00:17:05,035
A large crowd followed

334
00:17:05,346 --> 00:17:07,075
the opposition leaders.

335
00:17:07,348 --> 00:17:08,338
With torches in hand,

336
00:17:08,583 --> 00:17:10,312
they marched to the traffic circle.

337
00:17:11,052 --> 00:17:12,611
During the speech,

338
00:17:12,854 --> 00:17:15,050
the police began to encircle the crowd,

339
00:17:15,356 --> 00:17:17,381
and gradually forced them
into a small circle.

340
00:17:17,625 --> 00:17:20,424
A confrontation between the
police and the crowd ensued.

341
00:17:21,629 --> 00:17:22,152
The entire incident was

342
00:17:22,396 --> 00:17:24,490
later referred to as the
Formosa Incident

343
00:17:24,732 --> 00:17:26,097
or Kaohsiung Incident.

344
00:17:26,367 --> 00:17:28,335
As a result of the confrontation,

345
00:17:28,569 --> 00:17:29,832
official statistics show that

346
00:17:30,071 --> 00:17:32,267
close to 100 policemen were injured,

347
00:17:32,440 --> 00:17:33,839
but there was no reliable number

348
00:17:34,075 --> 00:17:36,305
of the injured civilians.

349
00:18:06,040 --> 00:18:07,303
After the incident,

350
00:18:07,508 --> 00:18:09,704
at 5 p.m. on Dec. 12,

351
00:18:09,944 --> 00:18:12,311
Formosa Magazine held
a press conference

352
00:18:12,480 --> 00:18:14,710
to clarify the events leading
to the confrontation.

353
00:18:14,949 --> 00:18:16,542
The Magazine believed
that the civilians

354
00:18:16,784 --> 00:18:18,377
were suppressed even before
any violence had occurred.

355
00:18:18,619 --> 00:18:20,678
The police first sealed off the streets,

356
00:18:20,922 --> 00:18:22,686
then used tear gas on the civilians.

357
00:18:34,135 --> 00:18:35,296
In early morning of Dec. 13

358
00:18:35,536 --> 00:18:37,527
Law enforcement agency
took swift action

359
00:18:37,772 --> 00:18:39,433
and arrested opposition leaders

360
00:18:39,674 --> 00:18:40,971
on charges of sedition.

361
00:18:41,208 --> 00:18:43,973
Those arrested were Chang
Chun-hung,Yao Chia-wen,

362
00:18:44,178 --> 00:18:46,579
Chen Chu, Annette Lu,
Lin Yi-hsiung, Wang To,

363
00:18:46,814 --> 00:18:49,545
Yang Ching-chu, Chou Ping-te,
Chi Wan-sheng,

364
00:18:49,784 --> 00:18:52,446
Chen Chung-sin, Wei Ting-chao,

365
00:18:52,687 --> 00:18:54,416
Chang Fu-chung, and Chiu Yi-pin.

366
00:18:54,655 --> 00:18:56,749
Shih Ming-de managed to escape

367
00:18:57,024 --> 00:18:58,287
before the police stormed
his residence.

368
00:19:05,032 --> 00:19:06,431
That day, a prosecutor
from the Garrison Command

369
00:19:06,667 --> 00:19:08,294
closed down Formosa Magazine

370
00:19:08,536 --> 00:19:10,004
and its offices in other places.

371
00:19:13,040 --> 00:19:14,030
On Dec. 14,

372
00:19:14,342 --> 00:19:15,707
the Garrison Command wrote
to the Legislative Yuan,

373
00:19:15,943 --> 00:19:17,604
and upon approval
by the Legislative Yuan,

374
00:19:17,845 --> 00:19:19,574
arrested Legislator Huang Hsin-chieh.

375
00:19:20,114 --> 00:19:21,639
The Garrison Command subsequently

376
00:19:21,882 --> 00:19:23,475
arrested scores of people

377
00:19:23,718 --> 00:19:26,119
related to the incident.

378
00:19:30,658 --> 00:19:31,216
After 26 days in hiding,

379
00:19:31,459 --> 00:19:33,223
Shih Ming-de was arrested

380
00:19:33,461 --> 00:19:35,793
on Jan. 8 the following year.

381
00:19:36,063 --> 00:19:36,723
During that time,

382
00:19:36,964 --> 00:19:39,331
Shih was branded by the
KMT-controlled media

383
00:19:39,567 --> 00:19:41,899
as an evil bandit.

384
00:19:42,136 --> 00:19:42,602
His picture appeared

385
00:19:42,837 --> 00:19:45,204
in newspapers and
the television every day.

386
00:19:45,539 --> 00:19:47,098
The KMT government
also announced

387
00:19:47,341 --> 00:19:49,139
huge rewards

388
00:19:49,377 --> 00:19:50,071
for his arrest.

389
00:19:50,311 --> 00:19:52,905
Shih's arrest became
an international news.

390
00:19:56,884 --> 00:19:58,352
When Shih was in hiding,

391
00:19:58,586 --> 00:20:00,213
those who helped and harbored him

392
00:20:00,454 --> 00:20:02,047
including Minister Gao Jyun-ming

393
00:20:02,289 --> 00:20:03,518
from the Taiwan Presbyterian Church,

394
00:20:03,758 --> 00:20:05,954
Lin Wen-chen, Chang Wun-ying,

395
00:20:06,193 --> 00:20:08,161
Shih Jui-yun, and Hsu Ching-fu

396
00:20:08,396 --> 00:20:09,921
were also arrested for implication.

397
00:20:18,773 --> 00:20:20,901
On this Thursday afternoon,
a murder occurred

398
00:20:21,142 --> 00:20:23,611
at the home of provincial
assemblyman Lin Yi-hsiung.

399
00:20:23,844 --> 00:20:26,313
Lin's 60-year-old mother Yu A-mei

400
00:20:26,547 --> 00:20:28,777
and 6-year-old twin daughters
Lin Liang-chun

401
00:20:29,016 --> 00:20:30,950
and Lin Ting-chun were murdered.

402
00:20:31,185 --> 00:20:32,346
This was an event
that stunned Taiwan.

403
00:20:32,586 --> 00:20:33,018
It was the morning

404
00:20:33,254 --> 00:20:35,382
of the court martial on the
Formosa Incident.

405
00:20:35,623 --> 00:20:38,092
In the morning of
Feb. 28, 1980

406
00:20:38,392 --> 00:20:40,417
A horrendous murder

407
00:20:40,661 --> 00:20:43,790
occurred at the home of
assemblyman Lin Yi-hsiung.

408
00:20:44,031 --> 00:20:45,590
Lin's mother and twin daughters

409
00:20:45,833 --> 00:20:47,494
Lin Liang-chun and Lin Ting-chun

410
00:20:47,735 --> 00:20:49,396
were murdered by

411
00:20:49,637 --> 00:20:51,332
unknown intruders.

412
00:20:51,772 --> 00:20:54,707
Lin Huan-chun, the eldest
daughter was seriously hurt.

413
00:20:55,076 --> 00:20:57,909
The murders stunned local
and overseas communities.

414
00:20:58,145 --> 00:21:00,443
Still hurting from earlier setbacks,

415
00:21:00,681 --> 00:21:02,809
the opposition plunged
further into deep despair.

416
00:21:09,390 --> 00:21:11,154
On April 18, 1980,

417
00:21:11,392 --> 00:21:12,860
the military court of the
Taiwan Garrison Command

418
00:21:13,094 --> 00:21:15,256
sentenced Shih to life imprisonment,

419
00:21:15,496 --> 00:21:17,430
Huang Hsin-chieh
to 14 years imprisonment,

420
00:21:18,566 --> 00:21:19,931
and Yao Chia-wen,

421
00:21:20,968 --> 00:21:22,367
Chang Chun-hung,

422
00:21:23,003 --> 00:21:24,368
Lin Yi-hsiung,

423
00:21:24,705 --> 00:21:26,002
Annette Lu,

424
00:21:26,207 --> 00:21:27,606
Chen Chu, and

425
00:21:27,908 --> 00:21:29,307
Lin Hong-hsuan

426
00:21:29,477 --> 00:21:31,639
were each sentenced
to 12 years in prison.

427
00:21:33,047 --> 00:21:34,776
The first island-wide crackdown

428
00:21:35,049 --> 00:21:36,141
on the opposition stunned the nation,

429
00:21:36,383 --> 00:21:37,350
in particular the

430
00:21:37,585 --> 00:21:39,417
large-scale court martial
that followed.

431
00:21:39,653 --> 00:21:41,348
Under pressure from the U.S,

432
00:21:41,589 --> 00:21:43,216
the trial was made public
to the media,

433
00:21:43,457 --> 00:21:45,391
which drew the public's attention.

434
00:21:47,361 --> 00:21:49,557
The trial started on March 18, 1980,

435
00:21:49,797 --> 00:21:51,822
and lasted nine days.

436
00:21:52,066 --> 00:21:54,034
Each defendant appeared
in court and argued about

437
00:21:54,201 --> 00:21:57,466
the case of the opposition
and the future of Taiwan.

438
00:21:57,705 --> 00:21:59,400
Newspaper reports on the trial

439
00:21:59,573 --> 00:22:00,802
prompted the public to start

440
00:22:01,075 --> 00:22:03,339
deliberating Taiwan's political issues,

441
00:22:03,577 --> 00:22:05,944
which unnerved the people
even further.

442
00:22:12,620 --> 00:22:14,748
On Dec. 6, 1980,

443
00:22:14,989 --> 00:22:17,390
Election of central
government representatives,

444
00:22:17,625 --> 00:22:20,856
which had been suspended for
two years, was resumed.

445
00:22:21,395 --> 00:22:22,863
In the election,

446
00:22:23,097 --> 00:22:25,293
opposition candidates,

447
00:22:25,466 --> 00:22:27,298
promised to continue their campaign

448
00:22:27,468 --> 00:22:28,867
and followed the footsteps
of their predecessors.

449
00:22:29,103 --> 00:22:31,003
The opposition used this
as their campaign theme

450
00:22:31,172 --> 00:22:32,799
and were able to win public support.

451
00:22:33,040 --> 00:22:34,530
Their members were elected
through overwhelming votes.

452
00:22:35,075 --> 00:22:36,008
The opposition

453
00:22:36,210 --> 00:22:38,577
was thus able to recover,

454
00:22:38,812 --> 00:22:39,836
regroup,

455
00:22:40,080 --> 00:22:41,912
and enter into a new era.

456
00:22:44,885 --> 00:22:46,876
The defense lawyers at the
Formosa Incident trial,

457
00:22:47,121 --> 00:22:48,646
Yu Ching, Chiang Peng-chien,

458
00:22:48,889 --> 00:22:51,722
Chen Shui-bian, Frank Hsieh,
and Su Chen-chang

459
00:22:51,959 --> 00:22:52,755
joined the opposition movement

460
00:22:53,060 --> 00:22:55,529
after the trial,

461
00:22:55,763 --> 00:22:56,696
which rewrote

462
00:22:56,931 --> 00:22:59,127
Taiwan's political history.

463
00:23:02,570 --> 00:23:04,038
After the Formosa Incident,

464
00:23:04,205 --> 00:23:06,196
the democracy movement
gained momentum.

465
00:23:06,440 --> 00:23:07,339
Democracy in Taiwan

466
00:23:07,541 --> 00:23:10,340
reverberated and spread

467
00:23:10,578 --> 00:23:12,740
through elections and
street movements.

468
00:23:49,550 --> 00:23:50,176
The Taiwan people

469
00:23:50,417 --> 00:23:52,715
started to use election
and street demonstrations,

470
00:23:52,953 --> 00:23:54,478
to overcome political taboos.

471
00:23:54,955 --> 00:23:55,888
Social movements

472
00:23:56,123 --> 00:23:58,524
such as consumers
protection movement

473
00:23:58,759 --> 00:24:00,750
and the anti-Dupont demonstration
in Lukang

474
00:24:01,061 --> 00:24:04,031
initiated civilian action
of environmental protection.

475
00:24:04,365 --> 00:24:06,333
This was followed by the
women's rights movement,

476
00:24:06,500 --> 00:24:09,094
labor movement, student movement,

477
00:24:09,370 --> 00:24:10,895
veterans returning home movement,

478
00:24:11,138 --> 00:24:13,106
to the subsequent farmers' movement.

479
00:24:13,574 --> 00:24:14,871
The forces of resistance

480
00:24:15,109 --> 00:24:17,043
continued to surge.

481
00:24:24,918 --> 00:24:26,977
The waves of people power

482
00:24:27,221 --> 00:24:29,019
that resulted in massive protests

483
00:24:29,323 --> 00:24:31,189
shook Taiwan.

484
00:24:36,497 --> 00:24:38,192
The potential for social movement

485
00:24:38,432 --> 00:24:39,991
long bottled up inside
the indigenous people,

486
00:24:40,167 --> 00:24:40,998
at this point

487
00:24:41,168 --> 00:24:43,398
gushed like water

488
00:24:43,637 --> 00:24:45,036
rushing out an open dam.

489
00:24:45,339 --> 00:24:48,036
From the Kaoshan Ching Magazine

490
00:24:48,342 --> 00:24:49,810
to the Commission for the
Promotion of Rights of

491
00:24:50,044 --> 00:24:52,411
Indigenous Peoples
established in 1984, young

492
00:24:53,047 --> 00:24:54,412
indigenous intellectuals

493
00:24:54,648 --> 00:24:57,140
started a series of protests

494
00:24:57,451 --> 00:24:58,475
in an attempt to rediscover

495
00:24:58,719 --> 00:25:01,416
their traditional culture
that had been lost

496
00:25:01,722 --> 00:25:04,020
due to economic and
cultural impacts,

497
00:25:04,224 --> 00:25:06,386
and to rediscover their own identity.

498
00:25:19,740 --> 00:25:22,038
On Sept. 28, 1986,

499
00:25:22,242 --> 00:25:23,710
The Opposition Campaign
Assistance Group

500
00:25:23,944 --> 00:25:25,309
convened at the Grand Hotel
in Taipei

501
00:25:25,546 --> 00:25:27,742
to nominate its candidates.

502
00:25:28,015 --> 00:25:29,983
The Group decided to form the

503
00:25:30,184 --> 00:25:31,709
Democratic Progressive Party (DPP)
with the

504
00:25:32,019 --> 00:25:34,283
opposition candidates
as founding members.

505
00:25:34,455 --> 00:25:36,116
The establishment of the DPP
was an unprecedented

506
00:25:36,357 --> 00:25:37,483
challenge to the KMT administration,

507
00:25:37,725 --> 00:25:39,386
which had banned political parties
for four decades.

508
00:25:49,036 --> 00:25:50,504
New hope for democracy.

509
00:25:50,738 --> 00:25:52,638
New political party to save Taiwan.

510
00:25:52,873 --> 00:25:54,170
New hope for democracy.

511
00:25:54,408 --> 00:25:56,308
New political party to save Taiwan.

512
00:25:56,477 --> 00:25:57,740
New hope for democracy.

513
00:25:58,045 --> 00:25:59,638
New political party to save Taiwan.

514
00:25:59,947 --> 00:26:01,039
New hope for democracy.

515
00:26:01,348 --> 00:26:02,179
Since the establishment of the DPP

516
00:26:02,416 --> 00:26:04,407
in 1986,

517
00:26:04,651 --> 00:26:06,119
many political taboos of the past

518
00:26:06,353 --> 00:26:07,821
started to shatter.

519
00:26:08,055 --> 00:26:09,489
On May 19,

520
00:26:09,723 --> 00:26:11,623
Cheng Nan-jung started

521
00:26:11,859 --> 00:26:13,224
his sit-down protest
in Lungshan Temple

522
00:26:13,460 --> 00:26:15,451
to demand the lifting of martial rule.

523
00:26:16,063 --> 00:26:18,157
Many crowd protests,
demonstrations,

524
00:26:18,399 --> 00:26:20,094
appeals, self-help movements,

525
00:26:20,367 --> 00:26:23,166
and street marches appeared.

526
00:26:29,443 --> 00:26:31,639
Our response to the international...

527
00:26:31,879 --> 00:26:32,971
The elderly Chiang Ching-kuo,

528
00:26:33,147 --> 00:26:35,673
realizing that political freedom
was inevitable, made

529
00:26:35,916 --> 00:26:38,351
an important announcement
within the KMT.

530
00:26:39,319 --> 00:26:41,549
On July 14, 1987,

531
00:26:41,789 --> 00:26:44,281
President Chiang officially ordered

532
00:26:44,491 --> 00:26:47,051
the lifting of martial rule in Taiwan

533
00:26:47,327 --> 00:26:48,658
starting July 15.

534
00:26:50,030 --> 00:26:51,054
On July 14,

535
00:26:52,065 --> 00:26:55,194
The Legislative Yuan announced
that martial rule

536
00:26:55,436 --> 00:27:00,397
would be lifted starting July 15,1987.

537
00:27:01,041 --> 00:27:01,906
Mr. President...

538
00:27:02,142 --> 00:27:03,871
Waves after waves of
civil movement

539
00:27:04,111 --> 00:27:04,634
finally put an end

540
00:27:04,878 --> 00:27:07,472
to the world's longest martial rule.

541
00:27:07,714 --> 00:27:10,376
After 38-years of martial rule,

542
00:27:10,617 --> 00:27:12,642
the ban on citizens to visit relatives
in China

543
00:27:12,886 --> 00:27:14,354
and the newspaper ban
were also lifted.

544
00:27:14,588 --> 00:27:17,023
Taiwan was finally able to
implement true democracy

545
00:27:17,224 --> 00:27:18,589
and take a giant stride forward.

546
00:27:40,881 --> 00:27:42,042
In 1988,

547
00:27:42,316 --> 00:27:45,047
Chiang, who had long
suffered from diabetes,

548
00:27:45,319 --> 00:27:46,980
passed away at 3:50 p.m.

549
00:27:47,154 --> 00:27:49,555
on Jan. 13.

550
00:28:00,601 --> 00:28:02,433
Vice-president Lee Teng-hui

551
00:28:02,669 --> 00:28:03,864
was duly sworn in as the

552
00:28:04,104 --> 00:28:07,005
7th president of the R.O.C.

553
00:28:10,043 --> 00:28:13,013
I pledged my allegiance

554
00:28:13,247 --> 00:28:15,716
to the people of Taiwan...

555
00:28:15,949 --> 00:28:18,646
Lee was born in Sanchih Township,
Taipei County.

556
00:28:18,886 --> 00:28:20,911
While he was studying at the
Kyoto Imperial University,

557
00:28:21,154 --> 00:28:22,144
Japan lost the war with China.

558
00:28:22,389 --> 00:28:24,448
Lee later studied agriculture
economics at NTU.

559
00:28:24,958 --> 00:28:26,722
As a scholar of agriculture economics,

560
00:28:26,994 --> 00:28:28,655
he was groomed by Chiang Ching-kuo

561
00:28:28,896 --> 00:28:30,830
and served as minister
without portfolio

562
00:28:31,064 --> 00:28:32,554
and later, vice-president.

563
00:28:32,833 --> 00:28:35,165
After Lee became president,

564
00:28:35,402 --> 00:28:36,961
public demand for reform

565
00:28:37,204 --> 00:28:39,639
increased.

566
00:28:41,775 --> 00:28:43,174
In January 1989,

567
00:28:43,410 --> 00:28:45,742
Cheng Nan-jung, who once
launched the 519 Green Action

568
00:28:46,013 --> 00:28:47,777
to promote total freedom of speech

569
00:28:48,015 --> 00:28:50,985
and founder of Freedom Era Weekly,

570
00:28:51,184 --> 00:28:52,982
published the new Taiwan
constitution

571
00:28:53,220 --> 00:28:54,984
drafted by Prof. Hsu Shih-kai

572
00:28:55,222 --> 00:28:56,280
and was charged with insurrection

573
00:28:56,490 --> 00:28:58,481
by the government.

574
00:28:59,326 --> 00:29:01,454
Cheng refused to appear in court,

575
00:29:01,695 --> 00:29:02,662
and confined himself in the

576
00:29:02,896 --> 00:29:05,831
publishing office for 71 days.

577
00:29:06,333 --> 00:29:07,198
On April 7, the police

578
00:29:07,434 --> 00:29:10,597
surrounded the publishing
office ready to arrest him.

579
00:29:10,837 --> 00:29:13,363
Cheng lighted the gasoline
he had prepared in advance

580
00:29:13,607 --> 00:29:14,699
and set himself on fire.

581
00:29:14,942 --> 00:29:16,341
His self-immolation
stunned the nation.

582
00:29:57,751 --> 00:29:58,684
During Cheng's farewell rites
on May 19,

583
00:29:58,919 --> 00:30:00,216
the procession reached

584
00:30:00,454 --> 00:30:03,355
the Office of the President,

585
00:30:03,624 --> 00:30:05,388
and the spirit of opposition movement

586
00:30:05,626 --> 00:30:07,355
in Taiwan reached its peak.

587
00:30:07,594 --> 00:30:10,461
This was a test for the
new president Lee.

588
00:30:10,831 --> 00:30:13,232
This same year, the Berlin Wall fell

589
00:30:13,467 --> 00:30:15,561
and the Cold War ended.

590
00:30:15,802 --> 00:30:17,930
A new world order had begun.

591
00:30:18,271 --> 00:30:21,536
A new order was starting
to take shape in Taiwan.

592
00:30:21,808 --> 00:30:22,900
In 1990,

593
00:30:23,143 --> 00:30:25,077
A faction within the KMT refused to

594
00:30:25,312 --> 00:30:28,077
accept Lee's leadership and policy.

595
00:30:28,415 --> 00:30:29,883
In February 1990, during the
election of the 8th president

596
00:30:30,117 --> 00:30:32,211
at the National Assembly,
which was composed of

597
00:30:32,452 --> 00:30:34,079
representatives elected on the mainland,

598
00:30:34,354 --> 00:30:37,324
confrontation between Lee and
the non-mainstream faction erupted.

599
00:30:37,524 --> 00:30:39,322
This was the political
infighting in February 1988.

600
00:30:40,160 --> 00:30:41,321
Also, the National Assembly
passed the amendment to

601
00:30:41,561 --> 00:30:43,120
the Temporary Provisions,
which extended the tenure

602
00:30:43,363 --> 00:30:45,331
of the National Assembly
representatives.

603
00:30:45,532 --> 00:30:46,465
The amendment contradicted
the people's will

604
00:30:46,700 --> 00:30:48,065
and gave more power
to the representatives.

605
00:30:48,368 --> 00:30:50,336
Thus, it led to the March
1990 Student Movement.

606
00:30:55,475 --> 00:30:56,499
Dissolve the National Assembly!

607
00:30:56,743 --> 00:30:58,711
Dissolve the National Assembly!

608
00:30:59,146 --> 00:31:00,841
Abolish the Temporary Provisions!

609
00:31:01,081 --> 00:31:02,879
Abolish the Temporary Provisions!

610
00:31:03,383 --> 00:31:05,044
Convene a national affairs conference!

611
00:31:05,252 --> 00:31:06,947
Convene a national affairs conference!

612
00:31:08,522 --> 00:31:09,956
In March 1990,

613
00:31:10,190 --> 00:31:11,954
thousands of college students

614
00:31:12,192 --> 00:31:14,388
gathered for a sit-down
at the CKS Memorial Hall

615
00:31:14,628 --> 00:31:16,357
to protest the abuse of power
by the National Assembly.

616
00:31:16,596 --> 00:31:17,927
The students demanded that
the National Assembly

617
00:31:18,165 --> 00:31:19,530
be dissolved, the Temporary
Provisions be abolished,

618
00:31:19,766 --> 00:31:21,063
a national affairs conference
be convened,

619
00:31:21,301 --> 00:31:22,735
and a timetable for reform
be presented

620
00:31:22,969 --> 00:31:24,903
in respond to the people's will.

621
00:31:25,605 --> 00:31:27,733
The students sat for five days,

622
00:31:28,041 --> 00:31:29,031
and President Lee officially met

623
00:31:29,342 --> 00:31:30,901
with the student representatives.

624
00:31:31,144 --> 00:31:32,737
The day after the meeting,
the student movement

625
00:31:33,046 --> 00:31:34,480
coordinating center issued a
statement to withdrawal,

626
00:31:34,715 --> 00:31:37,776
stressing its “unrelenting
pursuit for democracy,”

627
00:31:38,051 --> 00:31:41,021
The 6-day student movement
thus ended.

628
00:31:41,722 --> 00:31:43,816
In June 28, 1990,

629
00:31:44,057 --> 00:31:45,889
in response to the students'
demands, a national affairs

630
00:31:46,126 --> 00:31:48,618
conference was convened
at the Grand Hotel.

631
00:31:48,862 --> 00:31:49,920
A consensus was reached to
promote reform of the

632
00:31:50,163 --> 00:31:53,326
National Assembly and direct
election of the president.

633
00:31:53,633 --> 00:31:55,101
An further announcement was
made to terminate the Period

634
00:31:55,368 --> 00:31:57,860
of Mobilization for the
Suppression of Rebellion.

635
00:31:58,271 --> 00:31:59,739
The Period of Mobilization
for the Suppression of

636
00:32:00,073 --> 00:32:02,371
Rebellion was terminated
in accordance with law.

637
00:32:03,710 --> 00:32:05,678
On Dec. 3, 1994,

638
00:32:05,912 --> 00:32:07,243
the Constitution was amended
to allow for direct elections

639
00:32:07,481 --> 00:32:10,246
of the provincial governor
and city mayors.

640
00:32:23,897 --> 00:32:24,830
In the meantime, investments

641
00:32:25,098 --> 00:32:28,090
of Taiwanese businessmen in
China were increasing as lots

642
00:32:28,335 --> 00:32:31,305
of capital from Taiwan moved
into mainland China.

643
00:32:36,042 --> 00:32:36,508
Despite cross-Strait

644
00:32:36,743 --> 00:32:39,508
political and military stalemate,

645
00:32:39,746 --> 00:32:42,215
cross-Strait trade and
cultural exchanges

646
00:32:42,449 --> 00:32:45,544
increased rapidly after the 1990s.

647
00:32:45,786 --> 00:32:48,448
The situation was ironic.

648
00:32:48,722 --> 00:32:50,747
Communist China,
which claimed peaceful emergence,

649
00:32:51,057 --> 00:32:53,719
was alien to the Taiwan people.

650
00:32:53,960 --> 00:32:55,928
China was a socialist society
that went through Cultural

651
00:32:56,163 --> 00:32:59,098
Revolution and was actively
seeking modernization.

652
00:32:59,366 --> 00:33:01,767
Likewise, Taiwan awareness,

653
00:33:02,068 --> 00:33:03,126
which originated from
the island's history

654
00:33:03,370 --> 00:33:06,567
of immigrants and colonizers,

655
00:33:06,807 --> 00:33:09,333
was also incomprehensible to China.

656
00:33:13,780 --> 00:33:15,339
In June 1995,

657
00:33:15,549 --> 00:33:17,574
Lee Teng-hui's speech in the U.S.

658
00:33:17,818 --> 00:33:20,412
attracted international attention.

659
00:33:20,654 --> 00:33:22,622
In 1996, Taiwan finally held

660
00:33:22,856 --> 00:33:25,450
its first direct presidential election.

661
00:33:25,692 --> 00:33:26,591
In the run-up to the election,

662
00:33:26,827 --> 00:33:28,761
China conducted a series
of missile tests

663
00:33:29,029 --> 00:33:30,190
in the vicinity of the Taiwan Strait.

664
00:33:30,430 --> 00:33:32,592
Cross-strait tension was at its peak

665
00:33:32,833 --> 00:33:36,167
since the end of the Cold War.

666
00:33:42,609 --> 00:33:45,635
During the 1996 presidential election,

667
00:33:45,879 --> 00:33:47,847
the KMT became officially divided.

668
00:33:48,081 --> 00:33:50,448
Then incumbent President
Lee Teng-hui

669
00:33:50,684 --> 00:33:52,812
and then Premier Lien Chan

670
00:33:53,053 --> 00:33:54,384
represented the KMT in the election.

671
00:33:55,722 --> 00:33:57,622
Yet two KMT vice chairmen
left the party

672
00:33:57,858 --> 00:34:00,418
and ran in the election with
support from the New Party.

673
00:34:03,864 --> 00:34:05,662
The DPP for the first time
also presented its candidates

674
00:34:05,899 --> 00:34:08,334
for president and vice-president.

675
00:34:08,501 --> 00:34:08,899
Furthermore,

676
00:34:09,135 --> 00:34:11,035
independent candidates

677
00:34:11,271 --> 00:34:12,602
also ran in the election.

678
00:34:13,907 --> 00:34:14,601
During the election,

679
00:34:14,841 --> 00:34:15,433
despite China's

680
00:34:15,675 --> 00:34:18,372
military exercises aimed at Taiwan,

681
00:34:18,612 --> 00:34:20,341
Taiwan responded with

682
00:34:20,580 --> 00:34:22,708
a 76 percent voter turnout,

683
00:34:22,949 --> 00:34:25,111
with more than 14 million voters

684
00:34:25,318 --> 00:34:27,082
casting their ballots.

685
00:34:27,320 --> 00:34:28,287
Lee Teng-hui became

686
00:34:28,455 --> 00:34:30,389
the first popularly elected president.

687
00:34:30,624 --> 00:34:31,819
In over thousands of years,

688
00:34:32,058 --> 00:34:33,856
this was an unprecedented feat

689
00:34:34,094 --> 00:34:35,994
in countries governed by
Chinese people.

690
00:34:40,333 --> 00:34:41,164
In 2000,

691
00:34:41,401 --> 00:34:43,028
the direct presidential
election made possible

692
00:34:43,336 --> 00:34:45,498
the first-ever transition of
political power in Taiwan.

693
00:34:45,805 --> 00:34:47,466
DPP candidate Chen Shui-bian

694
00:34:47,707 --> 00:34:49,004
was elected the 10th president

695
00:34:49,209 --> 00:34:51,007
by a relative majority.

696
00:34:51,244 --> 00:34:52,439
This was the first transition

697
00:34:52,679 --> 00:34:54,443
of political power in Taiwan,

698
00:34:55,081 --> 00:34:57,015
signaling the end of

699
00:34:57,217 --> 00:34:58,309
the single-party leadership

700
00:34:58,518 --> 00:35:00,577
in place in Taiwan for many years.

701
00:35:00,820 --> 00:35:03,414
The DPP victory prevented
the further decline in Taiwan

702
00:35:03,657 --> 00:35:07,355
and allowed infusion of new
energy to provide the people

703
00:35:07,594 --> 00:35:12,031
with a clean and fair
political environment.

704
00:35:13,800 --> 00:35:14,665
In 2001,

705
00:35:14,901 --> 00:35:17,029
Taiwan was listed among
the nations in

706
00:35:17,237 --> 00:35:19,467
Freedom in the World,

707
00:35:19,706 --> 00:35:22,175
published by human rights
organization Freedom House.

708
00:35:22,509 --> 00:35:24,409
Taiwan was marked green in its

709
00:35:24,644 --> 00:35:25,975
Map of Freedom, along with

710
00:35:26,179 --> 00:35:29,171
the U.K, Japan, France, and Germany.

711
00:35:29,416 --> 00:35:31,544
Taiwan has continued
to press forward

712
00:35:31,785 --> 00:35:33,275
along the path of democracy.

713
00:35:41,161 --> 00:35:42,651
Over the past 20 to 30 years
in Taiwan,

714
00:35:42,896 --> 00:35:45,058
political reform and transformation

715
00:35:45,332 --> 00:35:46,390
have resulted in

716
00:35:46,633 --> 00:35:48,328
tangible democratic achievements.

717
00:35:48,568 --> 00:35:50,832
Yet there remained much room
for improvement in

718
00:35:51,071 --> 00:35:53,369
its democratic institutions.

719
00:35:53,606 --> 00:35:56,098
These include regulations on
party politics,

720
00:35:56,343 --> 00:35:57,902
quality of the legislation,

721
00:35:58,144 --> 00:35:59,771
improvements in the election culture,

722
00:36:00,080 --> 00:36:02,014
and upgrade of the education system.

723
00:36:02,349 --> 00:36:03,874
These are challenges facing

724
00:36:04,117 --> 00:36:06,313
the Taiwan people in the future.

725
00:36:27,374 --> 00:36:29,968
In Sept. 21, 1999,
Taiwan was hit with the

726
00:36:30,143 --> 00:36:33,169
largest earthquake in the last century.

727
00:36:33,480 --> 00:36:34,311
Measuring 7.3 on the Richter scale,

728
00:36:34,547 --> 00:36:36,743
the earthquake shook

729
00:36:37,017 --> 00:36:39,076
the entire island late in the evening.

730
00:36:39,419 --> 00:36:41,410
Many victims were buried by debris

731
00:36:41,654 --> 00:36:44,487
in their sleep.

732
00:36:44,724 --> 00:36:47,193
Damage was specially serious

733
00:36:47,427 --> 00:36:49,156
at the epicenter in central Taiwan.

734
00:36:49,396 --> 00:36:50,295
Over 2,330 people died

735
00:36:50,463 --> 00:36:52,989
in the tremor.

736
00:36:54,234 --> 00:36:55,065
The earthquake

737
00:36:55,335 --> 00:36:57,394
totally or partially destroyed

738
00:36:57,637 --> 00:36:59,332
over 10,000 houses,

739
00:36:59,572 --> 00:37:02,303
leaving more than 100,000
people homeless.

740
00:37:02,542 --> 00:37:05,739
Many public buildings were
also damaged.

741
00:37:06,046 --> 00:37:07,138
The disaster area extended from

742
00:37:07,380 --> 00:37:10,008
Taipei in the north to Chiayi
in the south.

743
00:37:10,250 --> 00:37:12,014
The quake was the worst
natural disaster

744
00:37:12,252 --> 00:37:13,378
and the most damaging

745
00:37:13,620 --> 00:37:16,646
in Taiwan's history.

746
00:37:19,726 --> 00:37:20,887
After the earthquake,

747
00:37:21,127 --> 00:37:23,687
the government and civilians
worked jointly

748
00:37:23,930 --> 00:37:25,955
in relief and recovery.

749
00:37:26,132 --> 00:37:29,830
Donations from the private
sector reached NT$20 billion.

750
00:37:40,213 --> 00:37:41,738
Relief goods from all over Taiwan

751
00:37:42,015 --> 00:37:44,279
flowed into the disaster areas.

752
00:37:51,324 --> 00:37:53,088
People from all walks of life

753
00:37:53,326 --> 00:37:55,727
volunteered in the disaster areas.

754
00:37:56,029 --> 00:37:58,498
They worked together with the military
and rescue personnel,

755
00:37:58,731 --> 00:38:01,200
digging and pulling survivors
from the debris,

756
00:38:01,434 --> 00:38:02,902
and finding places for
the victims to stay.

757
00:38:28,027 --> 00:38:29,256
The 921 earthquake
brought out the goodness

758
00:38:29,462 --> 00:38:32,261
and compassion of
the Taiwan people.

759
00:38:32,499 --> 00:38:33,364
People joined hands

760
00:38:33,600 --> 00:38:35,830
to subsist the crisis
with a steadfast attitude.

761
00:38:36,102 --> 00:38:37,399
In a few years,

762
00:38:37,637 --> 00:38:40,470
reconstruction work has been
mostly completed.

763
00:39:03,329 --> 00:39:05,024
After the 1990s,

764
00:39:05,331 --> 00:39:06,389
Taiwan experienced another

765
00:39:06,633 --> 00:39:08,067
economic breakthrough.

766
00:39:08,334 --> 00:39:10,302
The business sector and
the KMT government

767
00:39:10,470 --> 00:39:13,303
actively promoted IT applications.

768
00:39:13,540 --> 00:39:15,736
Taiwan transformed from
a major IT manufacturer

769
00:39:16,042 --> 00:39:18,101
to a major player in IT applications.

770
00:39:18,344 --> 00:39:20,506
Taiwan has finally entered
the IT Age.

771
00:39:21,047 --> 00:39:22,572
Inspired by the success of

772
00:39:22,815 --> 00:39:24,476
the Hsinchu Science-based
Industrial Park,

773
00:39:24,717 --> 00:39:26,310
the Tainan Science-based
Industrial Park and

774
00:39:26,553 --> 00:39:28,021
the Taichung Science-based
Industrial Park

775
00:39:28,188 --> 00:39:30,885
were established in

776
00:39:31,124 --> 00:39:32,319
1998 and 2003.

777
00:39:32,559 --> 00:39:34,391
New industrial parks would
transform and upgrade

778
00:39:34,627 --> 00:39:37,688
manufacturing industry in
central and northern Taiwan.

779
00:39:43,636 --> 00:39:45,627
In recent years, the
development of private brands

780
00:39:45,872 --> 00:39:48,466
has become the trend
in the IT industry.

781
00:39:48,708 --> 00:39:50,642
Many subcontract manufacturers

782
00:39:50,877 --> 00:39:51,935
have undergone successful
transformation

783
00:39:52,178 --> 00:39:53,942
and created their own brand names.

784
00:39:55,081 --> 00:39:57,243
At present, Taiwan is
the world's third largest

785
00:39:57,483 --> 00:39:59,781
IT products exporter.

786
00:40:00,019 --> 00:40:02,386
More than half of the
computers worldwide

787
00:40:02,622 --> 00:40:04,488
are manufactured in Taiwan.

788
00:40:04,757 --> 00:40:07,454
Taiwan accounts for
more than 70 percent of

789
00:40:07,694 --> 00:40:09,219
the global foundry business.

790
00:40:09,596 --> 00:40:10,586
Taiwan is now

791
00:40:10,830 --> 00:40:13,458
a major player in the IT industry.

792
00:40:24,210 --> 00:40:25,302
Apart from the IT industry,

793
00:40:25,545 --> 00:40:28,412
advancements in the
traditional industries have

794
00:40:28,648 --> 00:40:30,673
resulted in the creation of
private brand products that

795
00:40:30,917 --> 00:40:33,079
are successfully exported
to the international market.

796
00:40:33,620 --> 00:40:35,782
From bicycle to textile industries,

797
00:40:36,022 --> 00:40:38,719
from butterfly orchids to fine china,

798
00:40:38,958 --> 00:40:40,153
as well as Chinese glass art,

799
00:40:40,393 --> 00:40:42,521
they are all internationally
well-known.

800
00:40:46,232 --> 00:40:48,200
Despite limited natural resources,

801
00:40:48,434 --> 00:40:51,369
Taiwan has relied on the
efforts of the government

802
00:40:51,704 --> 00:40:53,763
and private sector to rank number 5

803
00:40:54,007 --> 00:40:55,065
in global competition in 2005.

804
00:40:55,375 --> 00:40:57,571
Taiwan is the world's
17th largest economy,

805
00:40:57,810 --> 00:40:59,539
and the 16th largest trading country.

806
00:40:59,846 --> 00:41:03,339
Taiwan's GDP ranks
20th in the world.

807
00:41:19,899 --> 00:41:21,367
Geographically,

808
00:41:21,601 --> 00:41:24,195
the small island of Taiwan
is not really that small.

809
00:41:24,437 --> 00:41:26,633
It has an area larger than those of

810
00:41:26,873 --> 00:41:28,841
40 percent of U.N. member countries.

811
00:41:29,108 --> 00:41:30,906
Taiwan's 23 million population

812
00:41:31,144 --> 00:41:31,770
is larger than those of

813
00:41:32,045 --> 00:41:34,377
three-fourths of
the U.N. member countries.

814
00:41:34,747 --> 00:41:35,714
This country,

815
00:41:35,948 --> 00:41:38,815
whether referred to as Taiwan
or Republic of China, has not

816
00:41:39,052 --> 00:41:41,578
received fairly treatment
from the global community

817
00:41:41,821 --> 00:41:44,791
to become member
of world organizations.

818
00:41:52,665 --> 00:41:54,326
But just like in previous generations,

819
00:41:54,567 --> 00:41:57,400
the people of Taiwan remain
undeterred and resilient.

820
00:41:57,637 --> 00:42:00,470
The people of Taiwan
will not lose hope

821
00:42:00,707 --> 00:42:02,937
even in adverse situations.

822
00:42:13,786 --> 00:42:16,221
Taiwan's democracy and
economic development

823
00:42:16,456 --> 00:42:18,754
will continue to meet challenges.

824
00:42:18,991 --> 00:42:21,551
But the people of Taiwan,
unwavering in its pursuit,

825
00:42:21,794 --> 00:42:22,784
will choose no other alternatives

826
00:42:23,096 --> 00:42:25,292
but to resolutely move
toward the future.

